key "zhang2005thevalue"

\end_inset

 exploits the production-based model to seek why particular firms covary
 more strongly with the SDF than others.
 In particular:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Asset in place is much riskier than growth options, so value firms' assets
 are riskier because of 
\series bold
costly reversibility (i.e., asymmetry 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{-}/\theta^{+}$
\end_inset


\series bold
)
\series default
 and 
\series bold
countercyclical price of risk
\series default
 (i.e., time varying 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{t}$
\end_inset

, decreasing with demeanded aggregate productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}-\bar{x}$
\end_inset

).
 In bad times, value firms are burdened with more unproductive capital and
 find it more difficult to reduce capital stocks than the growth firms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus, value firms' dividend and returns covary more with economic downturns
 (i.e., I think we can write as 
\begin_inset Formula $cov(R_{value\, firm},m)>0$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In good times, growth firms invest more and face higher adjustment cost
 to take advantage of favorable economic conditions, but value firms are
 not urgent to invest in boom times.
 As expanding capital is relatively easy, the dividends and returns of growth
 firms do not covary much with economic booms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In bad times, the discount rate is higher (countercyclical of price of risk),
 so firms' expected value is on average lower than those with constant price
 of risk.
 Value firms want to disinvest even more in bad times, so the time-varying
 of risk interacts more with value firms' value, resulting in a high average
 value premium.
\end_layout

